		<hr size="1">I have read many of the post from all of the PvP servers and found that their is a recuring theme of greif killing, corpse camping, bored level 50+ chars. slaughtering newbs, ect.  I currently have 3 chars. on Sullon all of which are untwinked and newly created.  One of my chars. is a good wood elf ranger so I know first hand what it is to be repeatedly pked by chars. 40 levels higher than me.  When I get pked, it doesn't really bother me unless the frequency of my deaths makes the game unplayable.  When this happens I still dont let it bother me, I simply play one of my other chars.  I was talking with my brother, who also has 3 chars. on Sullon, about some things that could add an iteresting twist to the game and a point came up about practicing skills.  The idea was basically that if you didn't practice a known skill for a long time, you should LOSE skill points in it. Ater all, thats kinda how things work in real life.  i/e if you don't speak your second language, you become less fluent in it.  Well to get back to my original point, what if a high level char. did nothing else in their life but pk people 40 levels lower than they were and didn't do much else to challenge their own development?  I think that they would eventually go soft, perhaps even get a beer belly.  Along these lines, I think that unneccesary greif killing, corpse camping, ect. would slow to a trickle if people lost experience for doing so.  I dont think that they should lose a lot of experience for the occasional pk but they sould lose more as their griefing increases.  Since on Sullon it doesn't seem that points really mean anything, why not turn the top 20 negative points into the top 20 negative experience.  After losing a couple of levels due to casual greifing do you think anyone would continue to do it?  Maybe this would finally change the chars. currently listed on the the top 20 negative points so that I could be greifed by newer and more exciting players. One final note, there would be no experience loss if a fight was instigated by a lowbie.  Anyway, this was just one idea.<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
</tr>
